message_1:
What is the rank of the following matrix:

\begin{pmatrix}
1 & 2 & 3 \\
4 & 5 & 6 \\
7 & 8 & 9 \\
\end{pmatrix}

message_2:
To find the rank of the matrix, we need to perform Gaussian elimination and count the number of non-zero rows in the resulting row-echelon form.

\begin{pmatrix}
1 & 2 & 3 \\
4 & 5 & 6 \\
7 & 8 & 9 \\
\end{pmatrix}

Subtract 4 times the first row from the second row, and 7 times the first row from the third row:

\begin{pmatrix}
1 & 2 & 3 \\
0 & -3 & -6 \\
0 & -6 & -12 \\
\end{pmatrix}

Now, divide the second row by -3:

\begin{pmatrix}
1 & 2 & 3 \\
0 & 1 & 2 \\
0 & -6 & -12 \\
\end{pmatrix}

Add 6 times the second row to the third row:

\begin{pmatrix}
1 & 2 & 3 \\
0 & 1 & 2 \\
0 & 0 & 0 \\
\end{pmatrix}

The row-echelon form of the matrix has two non-zero rows, so the rank of the matrix is 2.
